rvingness Ethnographic Insights from Athens and Melilla -- tChapter 9 Moral Economy of Exclusion Cases of Childbirth on the Margins of Regularity in the EU -- tConclusion -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2fd2star  aExamining which actors determine undocumented migrants' access to healthcare on the ground, this volume looks at what happens in the daily interactions between administrative personnel, healthcare professionals and migrant patients in healthcare institutions across Europe. Borders across Healthcare explores contemporary moral economies of the healthcare-migration nexus. The volume documents the many ways in which borders come to disrupt healthcare settings and illuminates how judgements of a health-related deservingness become increasingly important, producing hierarchies that undermine a universal right to healthcare.  afunded by European Commission Horizon 2020 - ERC Project EU Border Care (starting Grant 638259)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aEmigration and immigrationxHealth aspectszEuropean Union countries. 0aHealth services accessibilityzEuropean Union countries. 0aIllegal aliensxMedical carezEuropean Union countries. 0aImmigrantsxMedical carezEuropean Union countries. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aCarillon, Séverine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFedyuk, Olena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGerbier-Aublanc, Marjorie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGosselin, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuidi, Caterina Francesca, econtributor.